<h3>Conversion Equivalence</h3>
<ul>
    <li>1 curie = 3.7 x 1010 disintegrations per second</li>
    <li>1 becquerel = 1 disintegration per second</li>
    <li>1 millicurie (mCi) = 37 megabecquerels (MBq) </li>
    <li>1 rad = 0.01 gray (Gy)</li>
    <li>1 rem =	0.01 sievert (Sv)</li>
    <li>1 roentgen (R) = 0.000258 coulomb/kilogram (C/kg)</li>
    <li>1 megabecquerel (MBq) =	0.027 millicuries (mCi)</li>
    <li>1 gray (Gy) = 100 rad</li>
    <li>1 sievert (Sv) = 100 rem</li>
    <li>1 coulomb/kilogram (C/kg) = 3,880 roentgens</li>
</ul>
<h3>Examples</h3>
<p>Example 1:  A radioactive sample has an activity of 2.6 x 108 Bq. What is this activity in mCi?</p>
$$2.6 \times 10^{8} \times \frac{1 Ci}{3.7 \times 10^{8} Bq} \times \frac{10^{3} mCi}{1 Ci} = 7.0 mCi$$
<p>Example 2: A major source of radioactivity in plant tissue is an isotope of potassium, potassium 40. The dose equivalent of consuming one average size banana is 0.1 uSv.  What is this dose in rems?</p>
$$ 0.1 \mu Sv \times \frac{10^{-6}Sv}{1 \mu Sv} \times \frac{100}{rem} = 10^{-5} rem $$